Functional interface:
Contains exactly one abstract method making it suitable for use with Lamba Expressions & method References
Rule:
-It has only one abstract method
-It can have multiple default methods
-It can have multiple static methods
-It should have @FunctionalIntereface annotation on it. (Optional but recommended)



Lamba Expressions:
Concise way to represent an implementation of Functional interface using a short readable syntax -      () -> {//implementation here}
-Design to reduce boiler plate code
-It replace annonymous inner class

Rule:
-If there is only one line then not need to add {}; EX - MyInterface m3=()->System.out.println("Shorter Lambda Use");
-If there is only one line and method have return type then not need to add return word also EX - Addition var2 = (a, b) -> a + b;
-if abstract method have only one single parameter then shortcut use EX - Square var2 = s -> s * s; || Square var2 = (s) -> s * s;

--------------------***-------------------------

@FunctionalInterface
public interface MyInterface {
	void start();
}


// 1st way
		MyInterface m = new MyInterface() {
			@Override
			public void start() {
				System.out.println("Anonymous Class");

			}
		};

		m.start();
		
		
//2nd Way
MyInterface m2 = ()->{
			System.out.println("Lambda Expression");
		};
		
	m2.start();
		
		
//3rd way
MyInterface m3=()->System.out.println("Shorter Lambda Use");
		m3.start();

