Stream API:


1.It is an interface
2.It has lot of methods
3.It process Data
4.Supports funtional style program


1. stream() - present inside Collection Interface. It convert any collection into Stream, return type is Stream<E>

2.collect() - Inside Stream interface which takes all the elements from the Stream and transform then into a final result, like a List, Set, or Map.

Intermediate operations:
They transform or process the data in a stream, but they do not actually produce a result on their own. EX - filter(), map(), sorted()

Terminal operations:
They triggered the execution of the stream and produces a final result. EX - collect(), forEach(), count().


-Once a stream in consumed, it cannot be reused. Terminal Oprations end the stream completly.

-Intermediate oprations are lazy loaded, where terminal operations are eager loaded.

--------------------***-------------------------
Ex-
var numbers = new ArrayList<Integer>(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6));

		numbers.stream().filter((num) -> {
			System.out.println("Filter called");
			if (num % 2 == 0) {
				return true;
			}
			return false;
		}).map((num) -> {
			System.out.println("Map called");
			return num * 2;
		});   //output --nothing

		//but when we call terminal method 

			//above same code
		.forEach(System.out::println);  //after add this line then above code also executed and output printed

